  "notes": "Nuosu / Sichuan Yi (ꆇꉙ), a Loloish (Ngwi) language of Liangshan, written in the Modern Yi script (Liangshan Standard Yi, ratified 1980). INPUT CONTRACT: native Yi-syllabary text (Unicode Yi Syllables block U+A000..U+A4C6, NFC); the official Yi Pinyin romanisation is NOT accepted as input. The script is a SYLLABARY: one glyph = one full syllable (initial + rime + tone). The map is therefore keyed on syllabograms, not letters, and was generated mechanically: each Yi syllable character's Unicode NAME *is* its Yi-Pinyin spelling (U+A000 YI SYLLABLE IT = ⟨it⟩), which is decomposed into initial + final + tone letter and re-spelled in IPA using the published Sichuan Yi Pinyin correspondences — 43 initials (b [p], p [pʰ], bb [b], nb [ᵐb] …), 10 finals (i, ie, a, uo, o, e, u, ur, y, yr) and the tone letters: -t high [˥] (55), -x high-rising [˧˦] (34), unmarked mid [˧] (33), -p low-falling [˨˩] (21). ⟨ur⟩/⟨yr⟩ are the two 'buzzing' (retracted, fricativised) vowels. LEFT OUT: the syllable iteration mark ꀕ (U+A015), which reduplicates the preceding syllable and has no fixed segmental value, and the Yi radicals block.",
